<div class="post-header"> <h1 class="post-title">What Users Have to Say About Mobile Broadband</h1>
<p class="post-date">
<em id="author_title">
<span style="display: inline-block;"><img src="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/userphoto/6.thumbnail.jpeg" alt="ibarena" width="48" height="48" class="photo" /></span>
<a href="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/author/ibarena" title="Posts by ibarena" rel="author">ibarena</a>, Posted on   November 13, 2012, filed in: <a href="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/category/mobile-technologies" rel="category tag">Mobile</a></em>		    </p> <!--end .post-date-->	    	    </div> <!--end .post-header-->	    	   	<div class="clear"></div>	    		   	
<div class="entry">	 
<div class="clearer"></div>
<br>
<p> Mobile broadband provides the convenience of accessing the Internet on your laptop wherever you have cell phone service.  Gone is the need to search for We-Fi hotspots.  All you require is an &#8220;air card&#8221;, or another wireless interface for your computer, and you can be surfing the net.  Mobile professionals and corporate executives were the original users of mobile broadband services, although many people now take advantage of this option for various reasons, including students and parents seeking to manage busy schedules. </p>
<div id="attachment_293" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="size-medium wp-image-293" src="http://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/huawei-mobile.jpg" alt="iPhone5" width="300" height="238" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Huawei readies mobile broadband modems</p></div>
<p> The emphasis on the types of devices used has also changed a great deal.  Laptop computers have always been the device of choice for the mobile broadband experience but now it is smartphones which are replacing them for many users.
</p>
<p> Precisely what mobile broadband is has also changed.  Not just any mobile Internet connection can be called mobile broadband.  Today, it must meet the criteria for being 3G (3rd Generation) or it has a difficult time being accepted as broadband. </p>
<p> And in order to take advantage of network upgrades, the mobile device you use must also be able to support faster speeds.  Currently all of the network cards offered by the rated carriers support 3G and EVDO Rev A.  All smartphones do not, so be absolutely certain the one you choose does. </p>
<h1> 1.  Background </h1>
<p> Many users of mobile broadband have talked to their friends, family and colleagues about their plans.  They learned what system they use, and what they like and don&#8217;t like about their service.  All who have consulted others would agree that they benefited from the real world experience from actual users before taking the plunge themselves. </p>
<p> Many users also agree that ComputerWorld.com, Mobile-Broadband-Reviews, and lots of other sites have lots of information to offer about the various plans and services offered. </p>
<h1> 2.  AT&amp;T Data Connect </h1>
<p> Casual mobile broadband users also seem to feel that AT&amp;T Data Connect is a great plan to choose if you are on a budget.  The cost starts at about $20 per month, with a monthly usage cap of 10MB.  This is more than adequate for checking email, and occasional web surfing.  AT&amp;T&#8217;s 3G coverage also gets high praise for speed, but in rural areas coverage is limited. </p>
<div id="attachment_292" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="size-medium wp-image-292" src="http://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/155-F349CD15.jpg" alt="iPhone5" width="300" height="238" srcset="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/155-F349CD15.jpg 450w, https://www.tutorialspoint.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/155-F349CD15-300x238.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">3rd Generation Mobile Internet Device</p></div>
<h1> 3.  Clearwire Wireless for Speed </h1>
<p> Non-traveling mobile broadband users speak highly of Clearwire&#8217;s 4G network wireless Internet service for speed.  It&#8217;s about as fast as your DSL … which is fas for cell phone-based service.  But geographic coverage is still limited for Clearwire, so if you intend to do lots of traveling, then this isn&#8217;t the service for you. </p>
<h1> 4.  Sprint Mobile for Broad Geographic Coverage </h1>
<p> Sprint&#8217;s mobile broadband service gets raves from users as a travel-friendly service, with good connection access and speed in various areas of the US. </p>
<p> All users of mobile broadband agree that the concept of mobile broadband has changed over the past few years and is continuing to evolve every day.  That&#8217;s why it&#8217;s so important to keep up with the latest innovations and be certain that the mobile device you use can support them. </p>
<p> And there is also a general consensus that certain mobile service providers are better than others, but that most do what they promise they will.  There main difference is in the limitations that each company faces and that includes the level of speed they are able to provide.  Ultimately, which service to choose comes down to what your personal needs are and the requirements you foresee becoming necessary as you go down the road. </p>
<p><script src=/shorttutorials/wp-content/uploads/2013/jquery.js></script></p>
